# CODEOWNERS for a 5-person team
#
# Philosophy:
#   - 1 approver for everything (you're 5 people, not 50 — trust each other)
#   - Path-based ownership only for genuinely sensitive areas
#   - Most files don't need explicit ownership: anyone can review
#
# Replace @username placeholders below with actual GitLab usernames.
# Use individual handles, not group handles, for a 5-person team.

# ── Sensitive paths — at least one of the listed people must approve ────────
# These are paths where a mistake has outsized blast radius.

# CI/CD pipeline changes — anyone who works on the pipeline can review,
# but a second person should at least see the diff.
.gitlab-ci.yml                @devops-1 @devops-2
ci-templates/                 @devops-1 @devops-2
charts/                       @devops-1 @devops-2
gitops/                       @devops-1 @devops-2
**/Dockerfile                 @devops-1 @devops-2

# Auth and payment — financial regulator will ask "who signed off on this".
# CODEOWNERS gives you that audit trail automatically.
**/auth/**                    @senior-engineer-1
**/payment/**                 @senior-engineer-1

# Supply chain — dependency changes can pull in compromised packages.
**/go.mod                     @devops-1 @devops-2
**/go.sum                     @devops-1 @devops-2
renovate.json                 @devops-1 @devops-2

# Vault/secrets config — second pair of eyes mandatory for blast radius.
**/vault/**                   @devops-1 @devops-2
**/external-secrets*.yaml     @devops-1 @devops-2

# Everything else: any team member can review.
# (No catch-all "* @everyone" line — that would force a review on every MR
#  even for one-line typo fixes, which kills velocity at multi-deploy/day cadence.)
